by denying children the opportunity to develop their social skills in a controlled and supervised environment. &#10;I do agree, but as I've already pointed out children learn a lot more at school than just how to pass exams and those skills are arguably more important than anything taught to them in class. The decision to home school may well be indicative of a dangerous &quot;blind spot&quot; in a parent's perception of their child's needs. This is enough in my view to at least flag up a need for closer scrutiny. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="809" language="en" documentId="864" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Danot" date="06 November 2009 2:27pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6743130" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="8" thumbsDown="0" origId="864" notes="" title="Ridiculous rules for home schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="230"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="231" end="414"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="415" end="809"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>